00":"1380–1400","1378–Female":"1378–Afdød","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1380":"1380","1459":"1459","1403":"1403","1400":"1400","1378":"1378","1420":"1420","1530":"1530","1453":"1453","1485":"1485","1430":"1430","1428":"1428","about 1450":"omkring 1450","London, City of London, Greater London, England":"London, England, United Kingdom","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Rowallen Castle, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Skotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Skotland"},"nl":{"1400–1450":"1400–1450","1430–1485":"1430–1485","1403–Female":"1403–Overleden","1450–Male":"1450–Overleden","1453–1530":"1453–1530","1420–1460":"1420–1460","1428–1459":"1428–1459","1380–1400":"1380–1400","1378–Female":"1378–Overleden","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1380":"1380","1459":"1459","1403":"1403","1400":"1400","1378":"1378","1420":"1420","1530":"1530","1453":"1453","1485":"1485","1430":"1430","1428":"1428","about 1450":"circa 1450","London, City of London, Greater London, England":"London, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Rowallen Castle, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Schotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Schotland"},"en":{"1400–1450":"1400–1450","1430–1485":"1430–1485","1403–Female":"1403–Deceased","1450–Male":"1450–Deceased","1453–1530":"1453–1530","1420–1460":"1420–1460","1428–1459":"1428–1459","1380–1400":"1380–1400","1378–Female":"1378–Deceased","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1380":"1380","1459":"1459","1403":"1403","1400":"1400","1378":"1378","1420":"1420","1530":"1530","1453":"1453","1485":"1485","1430":"1430","1428":"1428","about 1450":"about 1450","London, City of London, Greater London, England":"London, England, United Kingdom","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Rowallen Castle, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Moore","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>more</i> ‘moor, marsh, fen’ (Old English <i>mōr</i>), hence a topographic name for someone who lived in such a place, or a habitational name from any of various places called with this word, as for example Moore in Cheshire or More in Shropshire.","English (of Norman origin): ethnic name from Old French <i>more</i> ‘Moor’, either someone from North Africa or, more often, a nickname for someone thought to resemble a Moor. Compare   Morrell   and   Moreau  .","English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English personal name <i>More</i> (Old French <i>More</i>, <i>Maur</i>, Latin <i>Maurus</i>), originally denoting either ‘Moor’ or someone with a swarthy complexion (compare   Morrell  ,   Morrin  ,   Morris  , and sense 2 above). There was a 6th-century Christian saint of this name."],"variants":[{"name":"Moor","meanings":["English, Irish, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Moore  .","German: variant of   Mohr  .","Dutch (also <b>De Moor</b>): nickname for a man of swarthy complexion, from Middle Dutch <i>moor</i> ‘Moor’ (from Latin <i>maurus</i>), or a topographic or habitational name referring to a house distinguished by the sign of a Moor. Compare   De Moor  ."]},{"name":"More","meanings":["French: nickname for a dark-skinned man, from a diminutive of Old French <i>more</i> ‘Moor’ (see   More  )."]},{"name":"Morrin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot.","English (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Morin</i>, a diminutive of <i>More</i> (Old French <i>More</i>, <i>Maur</i>, Latin <i>Maurus</i>); see   Moore   2 and 3.","English: perhaps sometimes from the Middle English personal name <i>Morwin</i> (Old English <i>Mōrwine</i>, the first element of which is uncertain and the second <i>wine</i> ‘friend’)."]},{"name":"Mauro","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Angelo, Sal, Domenic, Giuseppe, Antonio, Carmine, Carmelo, Domenico, Gaetano, Nino, Pasquale.","Italian (mainly southern): from the personal name <i>Mauro</i>, derived from the Latin personal and ethnic name <i>Maurus</i>, borne by various early Christian saints and meaning ‘Moor, North African’. Compare   Moore   and   Moro  ."]},{"name":"Moresco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Primo, Gino, Luciano, Riccardo.","Italian:","(<b>Morésco</b>): from a medieval personal name or a nickname for someone from North Africa or a swarthy or dark-haired man, from medieval Latin <i>Mauriscus</i> ‘Moor’ (see   Moore   2)."]},{"name":"Morey","meanings":["Irish (Limerick and Cork): variant of   Moore   4.","English (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Mory</i>, a pet form of <i>Amauri</i> (see   Amery  ).","English: perhaps also a variant of   Moore   1–3."]},{"name":"Morrell","meanings":["English (northern): from the medieval personal name <i>Morel</i>, a diminutive of Middle English or Old French <i>More</i>. Compare   Moore  .","Americanized form of French   Morel  . Compare   Morell   3."]},{"name":"Moores","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cheshire): variant of   Moore  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"McMoore","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Moore   4, in which <i>Mac-</i> ‘son of’ has been prefixed in modern times to give the name (<b>Ó Mórdha</b> ‘descendant of Mórdha’) an unmistakably Gaelic identity."]},{"name":"Moro","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Mario, Alberto, Jorge, Lino, Luis, Luiz, Manuel, Ramiro, Adolfo, Aida.  Italian Angelo, Pino, Pio, Remo, Antonio, Ciro, Cosmo, Elio, Enrico, Geno, Giancarlo, Gino.","Spanish: nickname or ethnic name from <i>moro</i> ‘Moor’, from Latin <i>Maurus</i> ‘Moor, North African’.","Italian: nickname from <i>moro</i> ‘Moor’ (see   Moore   2, compare 1 above), also ‘black-haired man’."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘light; beauty; prosperity’, also ‘rank, power, royal majesty’, a byname of the goddesses Lakshmi and Saraswati. Also widely used as an honorific title."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Thomas Moore was born in 1400, in Preston, Lancashire, England, his father, Sir William Moore \"The Elder\", was 20 and his mother, Lady Catherine Aucher, was 22. He married Agnes Austin in Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1450, in Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1400–1450":"1400–1450","1430–1485":"1430–1485","1403–Female":"1403–Surnud","1450–Male":"1450–Surnud","1453–1530":"1453–1530","1420–1460":"1420–1460","1428–1459":"1428–1459","1380–1400":"1380–1400","1378–Female":"1378–Surnud","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1380":"1380","1459":"1459","1403":"1403","1400":"1400","1378":"1378","1420":"1420","1530":"1530","1453":"1453","1485":"1485","1430":"1430","1428":"1428","about 1450":"umbes 1450","London, City of London, Greater London, England":"London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Preston, Lancashire, England":"P